==College==
Rice started his freshman season on the bench,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admin.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/the-blessings-and-burdens-of-being-the-son-of-an-nba-player-in-college-basketball/|title=Blessings and burdens part of being the son of an NBA player in the college basketball world|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2010-11-25|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> but he played in all but one game for the [[2009-10 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball team]]. He scored in double figures six times, including the [[2010 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] second round game against [[2009-10 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]].<ref name=GRJGS10>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/45525/year/2010/glen-rice-jr|title=Glen Rice Jr. Game-by-Game Stats (2009-10)|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He had season highs for [[point (basketball)|points]] (17), [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] (8) and [[assist (basketball)|assists]] (4) in the March 2, 2010 game against [[2009-10 Clemson Tigers men's basketball team|Clemson]].<ref name=GRJGS10/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=300610228|title=Georgia Tech 80 (19-10, 7-8 ACC): Clemson 91 (21-8, 9-6 ACC)|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2010-03-02|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Rice earned ACC All-Academic team recognition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030310aab.html|title=2010 ACC All-Academic Men's Basketball Team Announced: A pair of three-time All-Academic team selections headline the 2010 All-Atlantic Coast Conference Academic Men's Basketball Team.|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2010-03-03|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Although he was one of four people to receive at least one first place vote for ACC Rookie of the year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030910aab.html|title=Jackets' Favors Named ACC Rookie of the Year: Freshman forward becomes 11th Georgia Tech player to be honored.|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2010-03-09|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=TheACC.com}}</ref> he was not on the five-player ACC All-Rookie team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030810aac.html|title=Atlantic Coast Sports Media Association Announces 2009-10 All-ACC Teams: Top three scorers Vasquez, Scheyer and Delaney named unanimous first-team picks.|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2010-03-08|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=TheACC.com}}</ref>

As a sophomore, Rice posted six 20-point games,<ref name=GRJsf3g/> but three times (all Georgia Tech victories) he played at least 10 minutes while scoring no points.<ref name=GRJGS11/> He started 23 of 31 games that year.<ref name=RJlGTpS7/> Rice ranked second on the team in terms of minutes, points, rebounds, assists and [[steal (basketball)|steals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/team/stats/_/id/59/year/2011/georgia-tech-yellow-jackets|title=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets Stats - 2010-11|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He ranked 17th in the ACC in scoring and 6th in steals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2010-2011/confldrs.html#conf.wki|title=2010-11 ACC Basketball Statistics|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Three times Rice had more than 10 rebounds, giving him three [[double-doubles]].<ref name=GRJGS11>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/45525/year/2011/glen-rice-jr|title=Glen Rice Jr. Game-by-Game Stats (2010-11)|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Early in his sophomore season, the {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets|school=Georgia Institute of Technology|title=2010&ndash;11 Yellow Jackets team}} was in the same Legends Classic Tournament as the [[2010-11 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team]], but since the Wolverines did not qualify for the championship game, he did not get to play against his father's alma mater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-forward-jordan-morgan-excels-again-and-glen-rices-dream-matchup/|title=Michigan forward Jordan Morgan excels again and Glen Rice's dream matchup fizzles|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2010-11-26|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> In mid January, Rice had his first back-to-back twenty-point scoring nights on January 16 and January 19 against [[2010<U+2013>11 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina]] and [[2010<U+2013>11 Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's basketball team|Wake Forest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310160059|title=North Carolina 58 (12-5, 2-1 ACC); Georgia Tech 78 (8-8, 1-2 ACC)|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2011-01-16|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310190059|title=Wake Forest 39 (7-12, 0-4 ACC); Georgia Tech 74 (9-8, 2-2 ACC)|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2011-01-19|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Later in the season, he posted season highs in rebounds and point in back-to-back games:<ref name=GRJGS11/> Rice had 12 rebounds on January 30 against the [[2010<U+2013>11 Maryland Terrapins men's basketball team|Maryland Terrapins]] and 28 points on February 3 against the {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Miami Hurricanes|school=University of Miami|title=Miami Hurricanes}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310300059|title=Maryland 74 (14-7, 4-3 ACC); Georgia Tech 63 (10-10, 3-4 ACC)|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2011-01-30|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310342390|title=Georgia Tech 57 (10-11, 3-5 ACC); Miami (FL) 59 (13-9, 2-6 ACC)|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2011-02-03|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

Following the [[2011 NBA Draft]] selection of [[Iman Shumpert]], Rice was the leading returning scorer for the 2011&ndash;12 Yellow Jackets. He was suspended for the first three games of the [[2011<U+2013>12 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2011<U+2013>12 season]] for an undisclosed violation of team rules.<ref name=GRJsf3g>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/7221853/glen-rice-jr-georgia-tech-yellow-jackets-sit-1st-three-games|title=Glen Rice Jr. suspended for 3 games|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2011-11-11|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/ncaa-basketball/story/2011-11-12/georgia-tech-suspends-glen-rice-jr-for-three-games|title=Georgia Tech suspends Glen Rice Jr. for three games|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2011-11-12|publisher=[[Sporting News]]}}</ref> When he returned to the lineup following his suspension on November 18, he assumed the role of a [[sixth man]].<ref name=RJlGTpS7>{{cite web|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/AP7c6a2382671d410eb3002a4711755d2e.html|title=Rice Jr. leads Georgia Tech past Siena 72-44|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2011-11-23|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> In his return to the starting lineup on December 3 against the {{cbb link|2011|sex=men|team=Tulane Green Wave|school=Tulane University|title=Tulane Green Wave}}, Rice not only posted his first double-double of the season with 11 points and 11 rebounds, but also had his first career 4-[[blocked shot]] effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=313372655|title=Georgia Tech 52 (4-4, 0-1 away); Tulane 57 (9-0, 7-0 home)|accessdate=2011-12-07|date=2011-12-03|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He posted his second double-double of the season on December 19 against {{cbb link|2011|sex=men|team=Alabama A&M Bulldogs|school=Alabama A&M|title=Alabama A&M}} when he tallied 21 points, 10 rebounds and 3 blocks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=313530059|title=Alabama A&M 54 (2-4, 0-4 away); Georgia Tech 65 (6-4, 3-0 home)|accessdate=2011-12-20|date=2011-12-19|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Rice followed that with a double-double in his next outing on December 22 against {{cbb link|2011|sex=men|team=Mercer Bears|school=Mercer University|title=Mercer}} when he posted 19 points and 11 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=313560059|title=Mercer 65 (8-5, 1-1 A-Sun); Georgia Tech 59 (7-5, 4-1 home)|accessdate=2011-12-23|date=2011-12-22|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> The ACC requires that a player play in 75% of his team's games to be qualified for statistical rankings. After his 9th game on December 22, Rice qualified despite the three game suspension and is now ranked in the top ten in points, rebounds, blocks and steals per game  plus [[field goal percentage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2011-2012/confldrs.html#conf.wki|title=2011-12 ACC Basketball: Overall Statistics|accessdate=2011-12-23|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=TheACC.com}}</ref>

==Personal==
Rice, Sr. is the all-time leading scorer for Michigan and led the [[1988<U+2013>89 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1988<U+2013>89 Wolverines]] to the [[1989 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1989 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship]]. He was also a member of the [[1999<U+2013>2000 Los Angeles Lakers season|1999<U+2013>2000 Los Angeles Lakers championship team]].<ref name=GRJsf3g/> Rice, Jr. has a younger brother G'mitri Rice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gastongazette.com/sports/south-41607-point-aaron.html|title=Prep notebook: South Point has another tie to Shrine Bowl|date=2009-12-16|accessdate=2011-11-26|work=[[Gaston Gazette]]|author=Gardner, Phillip}}</ref>

